  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 4.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They had no children.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " If they had left sons, these would have succeeded ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "to",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " their office, and to the headship of the priestly line. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "In the sight of Aaron.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " In his lifetime (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 11:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Septuagint, \"with Aaron.\" In the time of David the descendants of Eleazar were divided into sixteen courses, the descendants of Ithamar into eight (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 24:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Numbers 3:4",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Names of the sons of Aaron, the \"anointed priests (see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 8:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), whose hand they filled to be priests,\" i.e., who were appointed to the priesthood (see at ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 7:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). On Nadab and Abihu, see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Leviticus 10:1-2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". As they had neither of them any children when they were put to death, Eleazar and Ithamar were the only priests \"in the sight of Aaron their father,\" i.e., during his lifetime. \"In the sight of:\" as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Genesis 11:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
